data.value: Array from the aligned objects are suitable as input to mathematical operators, because along each dimension they have the same index and size.
. The default fill value is NaN.
Method for joining the indexes of the passed objects along each dimension:
"outer": use the union of object indexes
"inner": use the intersection of object indexes
"left": use indexes from the first object with each dimension
"right": use indexes from the last object with each dimension
when indexes to be   aligned are not equal
"override": if indexes are of same size, rewrite indexes to be   those of the first object with that dimension. Indexes for the same   dimension must have the same size in all objects.
, data in the return values is always copied. If
and reindexing is unnecessary, or can be performed with only slice operations, then the output may share memory with the input. In either case, new xarray objects are always returned.
Any indexes explicitly provided with the
argument should be used in preference to the aligned indexes.
Dimensions that must be excluded from alignment
Value to use for newly missing values. If a dict-like, maps variable names to fill values. Use a data array's name to refer to its values.
If any dimensions without labels on the arguments have different sizes, or a different size than the size of the aligned dimension labels.
